etymologies: early 19th century: from Latin competit- ‘striven for’, from the verb competere (see compete), + -ive

definitions: relating to or characterized by competition

examples.text: a competitive sport
the intensely competitive newspaper industry

definitions: having or displaying a strong desire to be more successful than others

examples.text: she had a competitive streak

definitions: as good as or better than others of a comparable nature

examples.text: a car industry competitive with any in the world

definitions: (of prices) low enough to compare well with those of rival traders

examples.text: we offer prompt service at competitive rates

etymologies: late Middle English (as a noun): from French confins (plural noun), from Latin confinia, from confinis ‘bordering’, from con- ‘together’ + finis ‘end, limit’ (plural fines ‘territory’). The verb senses are from French confiner, based on Latin confinis

definitions: keep or restrict someone or something within certain limits of (space, scope, or time)

examples.text: he does not confine his message to high politics
you've confined yourself to what you know

definitions: restrain or forbid someone from leaving (a place)

examples.text: the troops were confined to their barracks

definitions: (of a person) be unable to leave (one's bed, home, or a wheelchair) because of illness or disability

examples.text: he was confined to bed for four days with a bad dose of flu

shortDefinitions: be unable to leave one's bed

definitions: (of a woman) remain in bed for a period before, during, and after giving birth

examples.text: she was confined for nearly a month

shortDefinitions: remain in bed before and after childbirth

definitions: the borders or boundaries of a place, especially with regard to their restricting freedom of movement

examples.text: within the confines of the hall escape was difficult

definitions: the limits of something abstract, especially a sphere of activity

examples.text: the narrow confines of political life

etymologies: late Middle English: from Latin natalis, from nat- ‘born’, from the verb nasci

definitions: relating to the place or time of one's birth

examples.text: he was living in the south, many miles from his natal city

shortDefinitions: relating to place or time of one's birth

etymologies: late 19th century: from nates+ -al

definitions: relating to the buttocks

examples.text: the natal cleft

definitions: a former province of South Africa, situated on the east coast. Having been a Boer republic and then a British colony, Natal acquired internal self-government in 1893 and became a province of the Union of South Africa in 1910. It was renamed KwaZulu-Natal in 1994.
etymologies: from Latin Terra Natalis ‘land of the day of birth’, a name given by Vasco da Gama in 1497, because he sighted the entrance to what is now Durban harbour on Christmas Day

definitions: a port on the Atlantic coast of north-eastern Brazil, capital of the state of Rio Grande do Norte; population 774,230 (2007).
shortDefinitions: port on Atlantic coast of NE Brazil

etymologies: Middle English: from Old French flame (noun), flamer (verb), from Latin flamma ‘a flame’

definitions: a hot glowing body of ignited gas that is generated by something on fire

examples.text: the car was engulfed in flames
a sheet of flame blocked my escape

shortDefinitions: hot glowing body of ignited gas

definitions: a thing compared to a flame's ability to burn fiercely or be extinguished

examples.text: the flame of hope flickered and died
there's nothing like a holiday to rekindle the flames of passion

definitions: a brilliant orange-red colour like that of flames

examples.text: a flame-red Alfa Romeo

definitions: a vitriolic or abusive message posted on the internet or sent by email, typically in quick response to another message

examples.text: send out an unsolicited email and you could possibly receive thousands of flames

definitions: burn and give off flames

examples.text: a great fire flamed in an open fireplace
hope flamed in her

definitions: set (something) alight

examples.text: warm the whisky slightly, pour over the lobster, and flame it

definitions: shine or glow like a flame

examples.text: her thick hair flamed against the light

definitions: (of a person's face) suddenly become red with intense emotion, especially anger or embarrassment

examples.text: Jess's cheeks flamed

shortDefinitions: (of person's face) become red with embarrassment etc.

definitions: direct a vitriolic or abusive message at (someone) on the internet or via email

examples.text: your opinions and mine are probably different, but please don't flame me

etymologies: late Middle English (also in the sense ‘surpass, be superior to’): from Old French surmonter(see sur-, mount)

definitions: overcome (a difficulty or obstacle)

examples.text: all manner of cultural differences were surmounted

definitions: stand or be placed on top of

examples.text: the tomb was surmounted by a sculptured angel

shortDefinitions: stand or be placed on top of
